The absolute neutrophil count is below the normal range

Slightly low hemoglobin count
A slightly low hemoglobin count isn't always a sign of illness – it may be normal for some people. Women who are pregnant commonly have low hemoglobin counts. A slightly lower than normal hemoglobin count may be caused by the hormone fluctuations and blood loss associated with the menstrual cycle. Athletes, especially endurance athletes, tend to have slightly low hemoglobin levels as judged by general population norms. In many cases, a low hemoglobin count is only slightly lower than normal and doesn't affect how you feel. If it gets more severe and causes symptoms, your low hemoglobin count may indicate you have anemia. Iron-deficiency anemia is the most common type of anemia. The best indicators of your body's total iron stores are blood iron level and your serum ferritin level. Iron-deficiency anemia causes pale skin, increased fatigability, general weakness, shortness of breath (dyspnea), vertigo, brittle nails and hair, dry skin and mucous membranes.

MCH level is below the normal range
The mean cell hemoglobin per red blood cell has no independent value and always correlates with the MCV and MCHC. A low MCH (hypochromia) may be caused by: hypochromic and microcytic anemia (iron-deficiency anemia, anemia due to chronic illnesses);thalassemia; some hemoglobinopathies;
lead poisoning; porphyrin synthesis disorders.

Low RDW-CV
A low RDW is not consistently associated with any hematologic disorder. A low RDW means that the red blood cells vary very little in size. One reason for a low RDW level is macrocytic anemia. Macrocytic anemia is a blood disorder in which not enough red blood cells are produced, but the ones that are present are large. Another cause of a low RDW level is microcytic anemia. Microcytic anemia is a condition in which abnormally small red blood cells are present. In these two disorders, the red blood cells do not vary much in size because they are either all small or all large.

Eosinophil count is below the normal range

The White Blood Cell count is higher than normal
Leukocytosis (elevated levels of white blood cells) indicates an inflammatory process or acute infections – mostly bacterial ones. A high white blood cell count is not always an indicator of some disease – white blood cells respond to various changes in the body. For instance, stress, pregnancy or exercise may cause an increase in white blood cell counts (leukocytosis). A white blood cell count is generally slightly higher than normal in women before menstruation. Leukocytosis is not typical of viral infections (such as flu, measles, parotitis, viral hepatitis, etc.), in which a high white blood cell count indicates the development of bacterial and other complications, with the exception of viral respiratory diseases, smallpox and other viral infections.

High absolute monocyte count (absolute monocytosis)
A high count of monocytes (monocytosis) may be found during the recovery period after severe infections and is an indicator of infectious mononucleosis. It may also be associated with many infectious diseases, including measles, chicken pox, German measles, diphtheria, etc. Monocytosis may be indicative of severe infectious diseases, such as sepsis, tuberculosis, some types of leukemia, as well as cancers in the lymphatic system.

High number of eosinophils
An increase in eosinophils (eosinophilia) is most commonly caused by allergic reactions and parasitic diseases (especially parasitic infestations), and may occur during the recovery period after acute infectious diseases (especially bacterial ones). Severe and prolonged eosinophilia is typically caused by parasitic infestations; rarely by protozoa. Eosinophilia is rarely severe if caused by a parasitic infestation of the intestines. Eosinophilia associated with allergic reactions is generally mild, but may be severe in some rare cases, such as, for instance, bronchial asthma or angioneurotic edema. Eosinophils found in the blood in an acute infectious disease are considered one of the signs of the early stages of recovery and are a very good symptom. The percentage of eosinophils continues to grow during the first few days after recovery and may exceed the normal range for a short period of time (postinfectious eosinophilia).

High number of eosinophils
An increase in eosinophils (eosinophilia) is most commonly caused by allergic reactions and parasitic diseases (especially parasitic infestations), and may occur during the recovery period after acute infectious diseases (especially bacterial ones). Severe and prolonged eosinophilia is typically caused by parasitic infestations; rarely by protozoa. Eosinophilia is rarely severe if caused by a parasitic infestation of the intestines. Eosinophilia associated with allergic reactions is generally mild, but may be severe in some rare cases, such as, for instance, bronchial asthma or angioneurotic edema. Eosinophils found in the blood in an acute infectious disease are considered one of the signs of the early stages of recovery and are a very good symptom. The percentage of eosinophils continues to grow during the first few days after recovery and may exceed the normal range for a short period of time (postinfectious eosinophilia).
